en_content:
AGI -&nbsp;The silence of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on the death of Pope Francis has not gone unnoticed. Peggio still made the post published by the Foreign Ministry yesterday - "Riposa in pace, Pope Francis. May his memory be a blessing" - and then deleted from social media shortly after. A decision which aroused the condemnation by the Israeli diplomats themselves.
<br The initiative is linked to the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2025-04-21/papa-francesco-vicinanza-a-gaza-tensioni-con-israele-31022612/"> criticism of the pontiff against Israel</a> for the war in Gaza. Although he has repeatedly appealed for the liberation of hostages, Francis tirelessly condemned the war, accusing the Idf of "crudelity". In his last book for the Jubilee, he also speculated that "what is happening in Gaza has the features of the genocide," triggering the harsh reaction of the Israeli authorities.
<br The initiative to cancel the post of condolences and the directive on ambassadors not to sign the books of condolences at the Vatican embassies in the world was criticized by the same diplomats, in particular at embassies in Catholic countries, and triggered controversy within the ministry in Jerusalem. Some have warned that the move could seriously damage the image of Israel, especially among the hundreds of millions of Catholic faithful worldwide.&nbsp;
"We have erased a simple and innocent tweet that expressed the basic condolences, clearly because of the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2025-04-22/pizzaballa-gaza-simbolo-pontificate-papapapa-francesco-31040955/"> Pope <bruth/a> Israel's criticism for the war in Gaza" "We were given the direct order to cancel the tweets, without any explanation," said an Israeli ambassador.
"When we asked for clarifications, we were told that the matter was 'in review'. It is not enough, not for us and certainly not for the public we represent."
<br A senior foreign ministry official, quoted by Ynet, reported that "the tweet was published by mistake. We responded to the Pope's statements against Israel during his life and will not do so after his death. We respect the feelings of his faithful." <br> And if for Raphael Schutz, Israeli ambassador to the Vatican until last summer, "the decision is a mistake" - "we should not take account in this way after the death of someone", said at the Jerusalem Post - for the former Israeli ambassador in Italy, Dror Eydar, Israel should not send a representative to the funeral, because &nbsp;pa Francis "powered anti-Semitism" during the war.
